{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"ab6ede4f728768fd153b1d5c2b68ce980e5a16f13ece98521ae8f89dd48be897","slug":"pages.m12-behavior-of-sample-proportion-3-of-3","location":"/pages/168-m12-behavior-of-sample-proportion-3-of-3.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Behavior of Sample Proportion (3 of 3)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"168-m12-behavior-of-sample-proportion-3-of-3.md","url":"/build/168-m12-behavior-of--14ba586027b0594e4b660403a84add00.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"mstTnZKCBP"}],"key":"XOW8JnNy5R"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Apply the sampling distribution of the sample proportion (when appropriate). In particular, be able to identify unusual samples from a given population.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"HhrJlqtfRl"}],"key":"KfyLjelxih"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If a sampling distribution is normally shaped, then we can apply the Standard Deviation Rule and use z-scores to determine probabilities. Let’s look at some examples.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"pxNyNcsba4"}],"key":"PrfeZum7V7"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"giPA5QD1cC"}],"key":"bOsinMUK0A"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"A random sample of 100 students is taken from the population of all part-time students in the United States, for which the overall proportion of females is .6.\n\n(a) There is a 95% chance that the sample proportion ($\\hat{p}$) falls between what two values? First note that the distribution of $\\hat{p}$ has the mean p = .6, standard deviation $\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{0.6(1-0.6)}{100}}=0.05$, and a shape that is close to normal, since np = 100(.6) = 60 and n(1 - p) = 100(.4) = 40 are both greater than 10. The Standard Deviation Rule applies: the probability is approximately .95 that $\\hat{p}$ falls within 2 standard deviations of the mean, that is, between 0.6 - 2(.05) and 0.6 + 2(.05). There is roughly a 95% chance that $\\hat{p}$ falls in the interval (.5, .7).\n\n(b) What is the probability that sample proportion $\\hat{p}$ is less than or equal to .56?\n\nTo find $P(\\hat{p}\\leq0.56)$, we standardize .56 to z = (.56-.60) / .05 = -.80:\n\n$P(\\hat{p}\\leq0.56)=P(Z\\leq-0.80)=0.2119$","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"E7drp6z9MT"}],"key":"sKkQWAqv4K"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To see the impact of the sample size on these probability calculations, consider the following variation of our example.","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"key":"wXttp9JEjU"}],"key":"qTdX8bgEge"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"PD7vTH1udN"}],"key":"d4hzW7NXwG"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"A random sample of *2,500* students is taken from the population of all part-time students in the United States, for which the overall proportion of females is .6.\n\n(a) There is a 95% chance that the sample proportion ($\\hat{p}$) falls between what two values? First note that the distribution of $\\hat{p}$ has the mean p = .6, standard deviation $\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{0.6(1-0.6)}{2500}}=0.01$, and a shape that is close to normal, since np = 2500(.6) = 1500 and n(1 - p) = 2500(.4) = 1000 are both greater than 10. The standard deviation rule applies: the probability is approximately .95 that $\\hat{p}$ falls within 2 standard deviations of the mean, that is, between 0.6 - 2(.01) and 0.6 + 2(.01). There is roughly a 95% chance that $\\hat{p}$ falls in the interval (.58, .62).\n\n(b) What is the probability that sample proportion $\\hat{p}$ is less than .56?\n\nTo find $P(\\hat{p}\\leq0.56)$, we standardize .56 to z = (.56 - .60) / .01 = -4.00:\n\n$P(\\hat{p}\\leq0.56)=P(Z\\leq-4.0)=0$, approximately.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"key":"EZrSDcnfOk"}],"key":"sXxoI5nACQ"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comment","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"ZKcddbBjOD"}],"identifier":"comment","label":"Comment","html_id":"comment","implicit":true,"key":"gOGCkrMnkk"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As long as the sample is truly random, the distribution of ","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"G6WxK9qBSp"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\hat{p}","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>p</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{p}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.1667em;\"><span class=\"mord\">^</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1944em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"TegPKhNX6S"},{"type":"text","value":" is centered at p, no matter what size sample has been taken. Larger samples have less spread. Specifically, when we multiplied the sample size by 25, increasing it from 100 to 2,500, the standard deviation was reduced to 1/5 of the original standard deviation. Sample proportion strays less from population proportion .6 when the sample is larger: it tends to fall anywhere between .5 and .7 for samples of size 100, whereas it tends to fall between .58 and .62 for samples of size 2,500. It is not so improbable to take a value as low as .56 for samples of 100 (probability is more than 20%) but it is almost impossible to take a value as low as low as .56 for samples of 2,500 (probability is virtually zero).","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"qt78mcTNo4"}],"key":"ipUTyYmmHg"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The purpose of this next activity is to give guided practice in